english:
  title: Inscription on the Huayan Dharma Assembly at Heungwangsa Temple's Institute of Broad Teaching
  author: Kim Busik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Herein I humbly observe that Heungwangsa Temple was founded through the vow of King Munjong the Benevolent and Filial, who adorned the Buddha's work. The Great Enlightenment National Teacher illuminated the dharma's meaning there, bringing forth great benefit. Yet in the thirty years that followed, the teachings gradually faded, with none to carry them forward. His disciples, devoted to preserving his legacy, sought means to revive them. They invited the National Teacher's foremost disciple Gyeseung and one hundred sixty students to the Institute of Broad Teaching. Beginning this month on an auspicious day, they have established a Huayan Dharma Assembly to last three weeks. The elders gather continuously to expound the boundless ocean of teaching. By this merit, we reverently pray: may the dharma wheel turn eternally, may the nation's fortune increase and flourish, may wind and rain fall in harmony, and may the people find benefit and joy.

    Regarding the Ultimate Truth—the profound and wondrous One, the very source of all dharmas—the three sages achieve perfect fusion, revealing the meaning of the Great Scripture. Form and emptiness interpenetrate and shine; principle and phenomenon illuminate each other. Like Indra's net layered upon layer, like the seal of the sea-mirror manifest in every detail. Without such merit, even the accomplished of the two vehicles gaze in awe and cannot advance. According to its nature, even the ten faiths of the beginning practitioner blend seamlessly together. Surely, without a king's sincere devotion, without a teacher's wise proclamation, who could draw the scripture from the dust mote and cause the sun to shine upon the great earth?

    Reflecting upon King Munjong the Benevolent and Filial: in conducting affairs of state, he moved with such skill that a perfect ox appears incomplete before him; in faith in the Buddha's teaching, he savored it as one tastes ambrosia. The golden monastery, the jeweled temple—he accomplished great and majestic works. In the practice hall and dharma assembly, he eternally established the Huayan gathering. The Great Enlightenment National Teacher, born of royal house, transcended worldly glory and immersed himself in the joy of meditation within the Buddhist path. With diligent wandering to many lands, he sought wise teachers; having attained the supreme realization, he became a great master. With foreknowledge he awakened those after him; with right view he shattered false views. As sandalwood allows no common timber near, as the lion's roar subdues all beasts—he not only fulfilled his predecessor's intention but also repaid the debt owed to the Buddha of old.

    Alas, time flows like water without rest. The mountain crumbles and leaves nothing to revere. The disciple, humbly receiving the remaining blessing, has inherited the great foundation. Yet my virtue cannot soften hearts, my wisdom cannot illuminate the world. With people already troubled, what becomes of governance? Like carrying fire through dried timber, like urging a horse with a rotten rope—my only hope lies in joining with the people to seek blessing. There is no way better than taking refuge in Buddha to pray for his power. Moreover, the vow of King Munjong yet remains; the means of spreading teaching can yet be undertaken. We have called forth the foremost disciples from their retreat to preside over the lecture hall. The four offerings that adorn the practice are many and growing; the six periods of worship and recitation proceed with untiring devotion. Though the sanctuary's term approaches its end, still the practitioners do not withdraw from their earnest cultivation. Since good is performed without ceasing, reward shall surely manifest in times to come.

    Humbly we pray: may wisdom's grace fall like rain, may the Buddha's clouds overshadow us. As fortune flows like rivers and virtue renews daily, grant that my person may rest in peace, that I may enjoy heaven's gift of long life. May the nation and I celebrate together, securing the throne against falling. May the auspicious signs of the great pattern appear and calamities vanish. May the three fields flourish and food abound, fulfilling the dream-fish sign of the Odes. May the four seas know no war, witnessing the return of war-horses as in the Martial Success. From the near realm of our own kin to the far realm of the three destinies, may all be freed from the torment of the infernal abyss and all attain the body-land of Vairocana Buddha.
